{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dill_ver02/data/sn91068695/00279559307/1930050801/0185.xml":{"full_text":"MARION PROGRESS\nPUBLISHED EVERY THURSDAY\nBY THE\nMcdowell publishing co.,\nMARION, N. C.\nTELEPHONE 64\nS. E. WHITTEN, Editor and Prop.\nW. A. COLLETT, Associate Editor.\nEntered at the Postoffice at Marion,\nN. C., as second class matter.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES:\nOne Year $1.50\nSix Months .75\nStrictly in Advance.\nMARION, N. C., MAY 8, 1930\nTHE SCHOOL A\nPUBLIC ENTERPRISE\nIn no other public institution are\npeople in general interested as they\nare in the schools. This fact is alone\nvery probably the biggest reason\nwhy the schools of North Carolina\nhave made such remarkable prog\nress in recent years. That this intei^\nest is a healthy one and one that\nshould be encouraged is not denied.\nAll peopte should be interested in\nan institution that is spending pub\nlic money. They should know how\nmuch and for what purpose the\nmoney is being spent. In a recent\nschool exhibit, seen by the writer, a\nchart of the percentage of school\ncosts had been worked ont by a\nMath class showing the total income\nof the school and the way it is spent\nA great deal of interest-was taken\nin this particular exhibit by every\npatron that came by. Every patron\nshould have this information and\nschool authorities are becoming\naware that the public in interested.\nIt is impossible for school au\nthorities to please everybody. There\nare bound to be some who will criti\ncize no matter what course is taken,\nIf the school is being run' economic\nally there 'is a group who say that\nexpenses should not be considered\nwhen the education of children is at\nstake. If modern trained teachers\nand modern methods are used it\ncosts too much and the one respon\nsible for this expenditure should be\ndismissed. If matters of discipline\nare dealt with in a just but firm\nmanner the ones in authority are\nunreasonable. If little attention is\npaid to minor yifroactions, school\ndiscipline and school morale break\ndown and the public immediately\nbegins a just criticism. Destructive\ncriticism has never helped any per\nson or any institution. Our schools\nar not perfect and will never be so\nlong as teachers and pupils are hu\nman and imperfect. That as much\nprogress has been made is proof\ntha the majority of people are in\nnone of the groups mentioned.\nEQUALIZING FUND BRINGS\nEXTENDED SCHOOL TERMS\nRaleigh, May 7'.\u2014The sum of $1,\n184,353.02 has just been sent to the\ncounties participating in the School\nEqualizing Fund by the State Super\nintendent of Public Instruction, A. i\nT. Allen; it was learned today from\nhis office.\nThe larger portion of this amount,\n$1,074,658.82, represented the al\nlotment to 93 counties from the $1,\n250,000 Tax Reduction Fund appro\npriated by the last General Assem\nbly. The sum of $43,631.44 was for\nrural supervision, and $66,062.70\nfor additional teachers allowed 'by j\nthe State Board of Equalization.\nThis $1,250,000 Tax Reduction j\nFund 'was appropriated according to\nlaw for the purpose of reducing the\nad valorem taxes in the county-wide,,\nspecial charter and special tax I\nschool districts in those counties par-1\nticipating in the distribution of the\nEqualizing Fund which operate their\nschools beyond the six months term.\nThis is the first time the State has\nfinancially recognized the extended\nterm as a part of the State school\nsystem. By this act, say educational\nofficers, the State has committed it\nself to an eight months school term.\nIt is believed by State Superinten\ndent Allen that this tax reduction\nfund money will do more to reduce\ntaxes in the several counties than\nany other one thing. It will enable j\nthe local tax districts to operate the j\nextended term at approximately the\nsame tax rate and will equalize in a\nmeasure both the- tax burden and\nthe educational opportunities among\nthe several local tax districts.\nThe fund is distributed to the\ncounties for those districts with ex\ntended terms according to the same\ngeneral principles which govern the\napportioning of the Equalization I\nfund for the six months term, that\nis, on the basis of the districts's abil-j\nity to support its extended term on i\nthe same cost level as its six months j\nterm.\nNext Monday and Tuesday, at\nMarion Theatre, \"SPRING IS\nHERE\", with an all-star east. It's\na gay and entertaining picture you\nwill like.\nLOOKIN' 'EM OVER\nAs far as w&, can see, Hoover was\nright when he predicted a return of\nprosperity by May 8.. Everybody\nmay not be prosperous in fact, but\nwhat's the difference? Isn't every\nbody happy?\nHad you thought about all the\nmeetings, shows, feeds, games, am\nusements, and such like the people\nof this community have had, are\nhaving, and will have in a period of\nten days or so?\nOur dentists went over to Ashe\nville Monday to celebrate, and that\nnight the Legion Auxiliary met to\nplan something. Tuesday night that\nbig entertainment feature by the\nMusic Club and Marion's Own band\nbrought them out from hitherto un\nexplored qorners. And a venture\nsome couple got married in the\ncourthouse. We saw it.\nMidway attraction? commenced\nMonday, too. The badge, key, and\nring man at the bridge; a free medi\nj cine show, dear to the hearts of\nj small *boys, and big ones, holding\nforth in Happy Hollow spreading joy\nuntil tbe rain came. And after.\nWednesday night the best cooks in\nthe Baptist Church stepped orward\nwith a feed reminiscent of a Georgia\ncamp meeting before the Confeder\nate war.\nIn the meantime pool balls click\noff a lively tune along the Rappahan\nnock, while golf, miniature golf, and\nAfrican golf, have their following in j\nseason and out. Of course the Mar-\nion is~showing good pictures all the\nweek.\nThursday night all those who can I\nspare the time will gather at Lake\nTahoma, in relentless pursuit of that j\nwill-o'-the-wisp, a hand containing\nthirteen spades. It's going to be a\nbig event.\nCome Friday, the kids, lads and\nlasses, teachers and people, will ov\nerrun the athletic field to get a\nglimpse of the pageant staged by the\nteachers of the grammar grades.\nAnd Friday night the College Hobo\nwill upu and do things at Marion\nHigh auditorium.\nOf course there are a lot of other\nthings going on, some of which are\nnot for publication, so don't feel\nslighted.\nSaturday will usher in another\nMemorial Day, when vets of the old\nSouth will get a feed and proper at\ntention. Here's hoping they'll be\nhere many years yet.\nOn the fourteenth, next Wednes\nday, the doctors take the floor, when\nthe Tenth District Association meets\nhere. At the same time, dowagers\nand duchesses \"transfer their courts i\nfrom Marion to Pinehurst for the\nFederation meeting, accompanied\nby some of our most royal princesses\nAfter the ball is over we'll be\nlooking for a good fishing hole on;\nthe creek. If somebody will provide\na skillet maybe we can get the fish.\nWho'll cook?\nSCHOOL NEWS\nMiss Torrence's Hoiiie Room gave\na short but interesting program at\nthe Chapel period Friday.\nMr. Deal, of the Deal Typewriter\nExchange, Hickory, was a caller in\nthe Commercial Department of the\nHigh School Friday.\ni\nSummer School of Business, Com\nmercial Department of Marion High\nSchool, May 23-August 1. Plan to\nenroll.\nMajor ,CoIlett was roaming around\nthe high school Monday forenoon.\nGlad to have him visit us.\n\"A Box of Dolls,\" a Japanese Op\neretta, will be given by twelve girls\nselected from Miss McCall and Mrs.\nFleming's first grades, Friday morn\ning at nine o'clock chapel. This is\nthe first grade's contribution to\nNational Music Week. Mrs. Morris\nwill be in charge.\nMAKE MOTHER'S DAY\nTHE BIGGEST DAY\nJ^ext Sunday is Mother's Pay in\nall the churches, and elsewhere.\nMethodist, Episcopalian, Presbyte\nrian, Baptist, or whatever your\nchurch affiliation, attend the special\nservices arranged in honor of the\nmothers of America. Let it be the\noutstanding gathering of the year,\nand remember that each and everj\none may help.\nTO THE VOTERS OF THE EIGH\nTEENTH JUDICIAL DISTRICT:\nI anf a candidate, subject to the\nRepublican primary, for the Office\nof Solicitor. My opponents are al\ngentlemen \"of the first water\", bui\nI want your votes because I neec\nthe nomination. Vote for me and id\nyou need prosecuting, I'll do it. I'l\nnot persecute.\nC. C. LISENBEE.\n[field day and pageant\nTOMORROW AFTERNOON\nField Day exercises of the Marion\npublic schools will begin promptly at\n2:00 o'clock Friday afternoon, on\nthe athletic field. Athletic contests\nand physical drill will open the pro\ngram.\nThe pageant will begin at 4:00 o'\nclock, in-the following order:\nMay Day Song, First Grade.\nBees and Butterflies, 2nd grade.\nCat Song, First grade.\nRaggedy Man.\nWelcome Sweet Springtime, 6th\nand 7th grades.\nI Polly, Sue Sweeney.\nFairies, 3rd Grade.\nFlower Drill, 4B Grade..\nJ Other Characters^ 5B Grade.\nProcession, Flower Girls.\nMay Queen, Carolyn Dysart.\ni Crowning of Queen.\ni Spng, Away.\nFolk Dance. May Pole.\nAwarding of prizes, by Superin\ntendent Richardson.\nThe marshals are selected from\nthe 7th grade. About \"five hundred\nchildren will take part in the pro\ngram.\nJUNIOR WOMAN'S CLUB\nHAVING BRIDGE TOURNAMENT\nAt the meeting of the Junior\nWoman's Club, held at the home of\nMrs. E. R. Wells, with Mrs. George\nEarp and Mrs. R. C. Spratt as joint\nhostesses, arrangements were made\nfor a bridge tournament, which will\ntake place tonight, Thursday, at\nLake Tahoma Casino. Every member\nis expected to provide one table and\narrange for the players. The general\ndirection of ^affairs devolves upon\nthe ways and means committee.\nAfter the business meeting and a\nfine program had been concluded,\nMrs. Wells, Mrs. Earp, and Mrs.\nSpratt, served delightful refresh-j\nments, consisting of sandwiches,\nsalted nuts and punch.\nDANCING SCHOOL FOR MARION\nAfter completing three most sue-'\neessful years in the musical world of\nCharlotte, North Carolina, Miss Hel-'\nen Lonon comes to her home town\nto continue her work of art, \"Song\nand Dance,\" for the summer.\nMiss Lonon is known throughout\nthe entire county of Mecklenburg\nfor her ability and competency, and\nshe is the favorite \"pinch hitter\" to\ncall on for her programs, shows,\nminstrels and recitals, presenting so\nmuch variety and spice in them.\nThe young lady has the rare com\nbination of performer and directress\nand is considered unexcelled in hev\nwork.\nMUSICALE THIS AFTERNOON\nAT MARION HIGH SCHOOL\nA music-ale will be given this af\nternoon at 3:30 o'clock in the\nschool auditorium by the. pupils of\nMisses Burton and Gilkey and Mes\ndames Harris and Davis, in obser\nvance of National Music Week.The\npublic is cordially invited.\nMISS CATHERINE E. LUKIN\nFuneral services for Miss Cather\nine Eleanor Lukin were held Mon\nday afternoon at the home of her\nsister, Mrs. B. F. Horton, in West\nMarion. Interment was in Oak Grove\ncemetery. x\nSurviving Miss Lukin are her\nmother, Mrs. Ada L. Lukin, five sis\nters, and one brother.\nMRS. MARY B. EDWARDS\nMonday morning Mrs. Mary B.\nEdwards died at the family resi\ndence at Garden City, after a\nyear's illness. Funeral services were\nheld at the Clear Creek Baptist\nChurch Wednesday afternoon, con\nducted by Rev. Charles Ellis, inter\nment being in the church cemetery.\nThe husband, T. A. Edwards, sur\nvives her, with six children.\nCARD OF THANKS\nMr. and Mrs. E. J. Ross desire to\nextend thanks to neighbors and\nfriends for kindness shown during\nthe illness and death of the latter's\nmother, Mrs. Sarah C. Cannon.\nPromptness\nREPAIRING]\nilllililllll III!! I J\n*<\u20224\nWhen you bring your shoes to us\nyou can rest assured that you will\nget the best material that can be\nbought. You will get them repaired\nas neat, as substantial and as cheap\nas anyone can do it and use the\nsame grade of material and the\nsame quality of work that we do.\nCHAMPION SHOE SHOP\n14 E. HENDERSON ST.\nBANKS TO CLOSE\nMEMORIAL DAY\nIn keeping with the usual custom,\nthe banks of Marion will be closed\nall day, Saturday, May 10, in obser\nvance of Memorial Day.\nOASIS theatre\"\nTHURSDAY and FRIDAY,\nMay 8th and 9th.\nAT NIGHT ONLY\nSTAMIE SHAVER\nand his\nCOMEDIANS\nTwo (2) Days\nAlso Good Picture Programs,\nPopular Prices,\nWATCH AND JEWELRY\nREPAIRING\np\nI have opened my shop at\n20 West Court Street in the\nDavis Shoe Shop and give you\nprompt and expert service in\nrepairing watches and jewelry.\nCome and see me,\nW. L TWIGGS\nThe School of the Dance\n\nTrap Dancing\nA Specialty\nMusical\nComedy\nBallet\nAcrobatic\nMISS HELEN LONON\n\nStudio in Lonon Building over Tainter's No, 2\nTelephone 293 between 3 and 4\no'clock for appointments.\nDelicious Sweets\nFor Mother!\ni\n\nWhatever her age, Mother still retains\nthat \"girlish sweet tooth!\"\nAnd Sunday is the time to show her we\nstill think her the \"Sweetest Mother\nin the World,\"\nShe'd love to get\nWhitman's Fine Candy\nAT\nTHE REXALL DRUG STORE\nTelephone 286\nRemember This When Buying\nYour Electric Refrigerator\n\nOf the Hundreds of Thousands of General\nN.. C I\nElecrtic owners not One has ever spent One\n\nCent for repairs or service.\nGENERAL ELECTRIC\nRefrigerator\nNational Utilities Co. of N. C.","height":"33300","width":"22516"}}
